title: Leopard Lioness: Leo Laying
caption: Were you aware that there is such a thing as a leopard x lion mix?  This Panthera Hybrid is named a Leopon.  My solar + lunar signs are Leo, the Lion, and my birth month is August.  The dress I chose to represent my sensual, sleek feline attributes was a satin leopard print with a matching pair of designer sunglasses to add mystery.  I added leather gloves + shoes to accompany the outfit as well as a sharp crop, to ensure a stinging bite.

title: Garnet + Guard:  Any Good News?
caption: Garnet is the January birth stone and the crimson, pink, gold, and green colors are a nice bridge from the holiday season.  Red is also a symbol for good luck and happiness in Chinese culture.  This calendar year celebrates the year of the dog in the Chinese Zodiac, hence my guard pup~  This is a story on how the Mistress lead us form the garden into the building, up the hotel, and into a room where the sensuality can finally occur behind closed doors…

title: MONUMENT TO THE UNCOUPLE
caption: Through this performance score, I want to explore what it means to be uncoupled; what exactly constructs a union if that union isn’t ratified by the state? If we aren’t interested in engaging in a marital agreement for the purpose of obtaining property, nor for the heterosexual bio-utility of production, then divorce isn’t about loss, because there was no property in the first place. Divorce becomes a celebration, an empty space from which the next evolution can take place; the uncoupling is the release from the container, a choreographed event of care, a maintenance of intimacy via deconstruction
credits: Photos by Junior Fernandez, featuring Anastasia Vayner

title: Unbound
caption: Unbound explores the inheritance of ancestral trauma. My great-great grandmother was the last woman in my family to have bound feet. At age four (the same age when girls begin the process of foot-binding), I spent six months living in my ancestral home in Kaiping, China, where I suffered a fracture to my left foot. I solicit men via Craigslist and Tinder for anonymous “foot worship” sessions in which they pay to rub, kiss, and lick my feet. I construct an altar to my great-great grandmother and invite audience members to sit with me inside a circle of rice and to trade foot massages as we share stories of family pain. Performed at performance space, Folkestone, UK, October 2019.

title: Starfire
caption: In “Starfire”, I use menstruation as the basis for a feminist reenactment of the Holy Eucharist. I appear as the Scarlet Woman, who transforms the profane into the sacred by reimagining religious rituals from a feminist perspective.

title: Nurture
caption: Nurture presents motherhood as a durational performance and as an act of love and labor. In the role of the archetypal Mother, the artist offers her empathy and her body to the audience in an intimate, one-on-one interaction. Holding participants in her arms so that they may suckle from her breast, she plays a soundtrack of lullabies sung by mothers in different languages, while inviting them to discuss their thoughts about their mothers or motherhood. Performed at Tempting Failure Biennial of Performance Art and Noise, London, UK, July 2018.
credits: Collaborators: Molly Caitlin Baber & Jack Murphy

title: Purify
caption: Rope, fire, blood, earth, wood, water, wax, metal. Audience members write down their fears and sins on slips of paper, which are tucked under ropes that bind my body. The papers are read aloud and burned as the artists shed their blood in a cleansing ritual. Performed at Gelegenheiten, Berlin, Germany, March 2019.
credits:
Collaborators: Zarahlena
Cristina Söderström Martos
Chandler Barnes (ropes/piercing)
Bommi Pelletiér (music)

title: Play4UsNow
caption: A participatory online performance featuring an all-sex worker cast and crew which utilized audience members’ data as a form of intimacy and political critique. The multilayered performance begins at the first point of contact with our website (www.play4usnow.com), where users submit personal preferences and answer security questions in return for an invitation to the "data dungeon". Using the aesthetics of the underground BDSM dungeon and employing real-life sex workers impacted by data policy, the project engaged viewers to critically consider their experience of digital surveillance and privacy.

title: Human Flesh
caption:
Human Flesh

She was a a doomed angel with more love for humanity than even her immortal body could contain. Daily she would listen to the reverence of humankind and shower it with her otherworldly affection. On the day she burst, she could no longer hear their prayers. They had forgotten her. She condemned those mortals, and shed her ethereal form to reveal the fanatical, vengeful creature beneath. She could not die, so she traipsed the surface of the earth, wailing, mourning humankind’s unrequited love.

She was monstrous.
credits: Collaboration with Kathryn Kane. Wardrobe Lasegue.falret.

title: Homunculus
caption: How the body is viewed informs us on the ways that the dynamics of power alter relationships between people and the individual’s object-subject-hood. Objectification is often a process that female bodies are subjected to, losing agency and empathy in the process. By abstracting and deconstructing the male form, I remove its usual role as “subject,” allowing for a new context in which to view the male body.

title: L’Origine du Monde
caption: I'm interested in re-contextualizing the narratives of sexual labor. Here, the only body visible is of the (presumed) client, headless, anonymous, but offering a brief glimpse into a moment of intimacy through the eyes of a sex worker. A visual shift in the cultural script of sexual commerce.

title: Black Women Invented Modern Stripping and Pole Dance
caption:
Inspired by a tweet by @sequinmicrobikini ✨ Black lives matter should be an integral part of any SW’s belief system. Black sex workers have always been at the frontlines of police violence, discrimination and amplified danger of stigmatized work. Despite this, black sex workers have been incredibly resilient and have created a beautiful and intricate culture surrounding sex work. I’m so grateful for every black sex worker who has ever offered me a piece of advice on my hustle, fixed my hair for me, had my back w a customer, showed me a dance move, etc the list goes on forever. Non black SW -LITERALLY- owe everything we pride ourselves on to black SW. Its so important that we are regularly setting aside a significant percentage of our income to redistribute to black SW and organizations that support particularly trans and street based SW. You can donate to a relief fund for black SW organized by @thegizellemarie in the link in my bio. You can also donate to a mutual aid fund for SW of color via cashapp to $venuscuffs . I’m super excited to see what’s going on with the @pdxstripperstrike as dancers and other strip club staff are organizing to combat racism in the industry. There are so many ways to show up right now so let’s stay plugged in, stay active, drink water, eat a vegetable, and check on your friends. We need to stay focused to manifest a better world thru decriminalization, black liberation, decolonization and tearing down the raging machine known as capitalism ✨
EDIT: forgot to add- @doroshow (founder of G.L.I.T.S) is accepting donations for black trans women via her website. The link is in my bio as well!

title: Sticky Sweet
caption:
I feel like bubble gum is the perfect metaphor for how I feel being stigmatized as a sex worker sometimes — sticky sweet, bubbly odor, delightful but only for a short time, easy to spit out when you are done. Seeing people who don’t do sex work exploit our aesthetics, actively harming our communities without listening to our struggle makes me feel like chewed up bubble gum. Seeing people in sex work who have never done FSSW talk down on FSSW providers makes me feel like chewed up bubble gum.
Our community is in CRISIS particularly trans black and indigenous street based sex workers. Street based sex workers are on the frontlines of a battle that effects us all. Either step the fuck up for the most stigmatized sex workers or get the fuck out of our shoes, clubs, websites, and communities *AHEM* @bellathorne 😤😤😤
Also yes I did chew an entire bag of bubble gum for this
references: '@bellathorne made me angry enough to make this piece :-)
